1- Data Understanding

Data Collection

We will recover the database from a file, AssuranceExpertsInc.txt, containing informations about clients grouped by postal code.

DirtyInsurance <- read.table("AssurancExpertsInc.txt", header=T,fill=T, encoding="utf-8", sep="\t", dec=".",quote = "", na.string=" " )

Data Description

The columns are divided between sociodemographic columns, and columns related to insurance. Besides, the column names are not significant. Thus we have recovered the true column names from the descriptive file and we will assign each name to its respective column.

columnNames<- read.table("columns.txt", header=F,fill=T, encoding="utf-8", sep="\n", dec=".",quote = "", na.string=" " )
colnames(DirtyInsurance)<-as.vector(columnNames$V1)

2- Data Preparation

We have noticed that the modalities of each column range from 0 to 40, with each modality representing a certain real world modality. Our values are not ordinal, thus we will have to correctly identify every modality with its respective real world modality, and we will have to dummify our dataset.

Data Construction

First, we recover the customer subtype, and we will assign the modalities to the respective columns.

L0<- read.table("L0.txt", header=F,fill=T, encoding="utf-8", sep="\n", dec=".",quote = "", na.string=" " )
CustomerSubtypeDummies=dummy(DirtyInsurance$CustomerSubtype, sep = "_")
colnames(CustomerSubtypeDummies)<-as.vector(L0$V1)

Then we recover the customer main type and we do the same thing.

L1<- read.table("L1.txt", header=F,fill=T, encoding="utf-8", sep="\n", dec=".",quote = "", na.string=" " )
CustomerAgeDummies=dummy(DirtyInsurance$Avgage, sep = "_")
colnames(CustomerAgeDummies)<-as.vector(L1$V1)

Then we recover the average age and we do the same thing.

L2<- read.table("L2.txt", header=F,fill=T, encoding="utf-8", sep="\n", dec=".",quote = "", na.string=" " )
CustomerMainType=dummy(DirtyInsurance$CustomerMainType, sep = "_")
colnames(CustomerMainType)<-as.vector(L2$V1)

Now, we will have to get rid of two columns. STATUS says if the column is a part of the training set or the testing set. CLASS is our target value. We will have to skip both of these before we dummify the rest of the dataset.

isTrain=DirtyInsurance$STATUS
target=DirtyInsurance$CLASS
targetFactor=DirtyInsurance$CLASS
target=as.numeric(target)
CleanerInsurance<-DirtyInsurance[,!(colnames(DirtyInsurance)%in% c("CLASS","STATUS" ))]

Now, we dummify all the remaining values.

for(b in colnames(CleanerInsurance[,6:length(colnames(CleanerInsurance))])) CleanerInsurance[[b]] <- as.factor(CleanerInsurance[[b]])
Dummified=dummy.data.frame(CleanerInsurance[,6:length(colnames(CleanerInsurance))], sep = "_")

Data Integration

Now we integrate all dummified values into one dataset.

AllDummies=cbind(CustomerMainType,CustomerSubtypeDummies, CustomerAgeDummies,Dummified)

Data Exploration

We have little knowledge of insurance and we have little time to spare to understand the topic entirely. We could start setting assumptions but it will be a long process of trial and error we don’t want.

Hypothesis and outline

The idea would be to study the correlation between every single dummy value and the target value. Then, by plotting the top 10 most positively correlated attributes and the top 10 most negatively correlated attributes, we will be able to make a targeted vizualization, reaching directly the most important values.

Correlations

First, we start with the correlations

for(b in colnames(Dummified)) Dummified[[b]] <- as.numeric(Dummified[[b]])
correlations=apply(Dummified,2, function(col)cor(col, target))

Then we plot the most positively correlated attributes

par(las=2) # make label text perpendicular to axis
par(mar=c(5,18,4,2)) # increase y-axis margin.
heads=sort(correlations, decreasing=T)
barplot(head( heads[2:length(heads)],10), main="Positively correlated attributes", horiz=TRUE,names.arg=head(colnames( heads[2:length(heads)]),10),  cex.names=0.8)

Now, we plot the most negatively correlated attributes

par(las=2) # make label text perpendicular to axis
par(mar=c(5,18,4,2)) # increase y-axis margin.
tails=sort(correlations, decreasing=F)
barplot(head( tails[2:length(tails)],10), main="Negatively correlated attributes", horiz=TRUE,names.arg=head(colnames( tails[2:length(tails)]),10),  cex.names=0.8)

Now, we move straight to plotting the select values’ confusion matrices

Conclusion and selected attributes

Now, we move straight to plotting the select values’ confusion matrices

We start with the positive correlations

Positive correlations

Contribution to car policies from 500 to 999

counts <-table(Dummified$`Contribution car policies_6`, targetFactor)
barplot(counts,main="Influence of the contribution to car policies",
        xlab="Wants insurance on caravan", col=c("red","green"),
        legend = c("Has different or no policy","Has 500 – 999 car policy"), beside=TRUE)

We can see here that those who spend between 500 and 999 on car policies are more likely to want a caravan.

It can be explained by the fact that those having a car policy both have a car, have an expensive car insurance and thus have the ability and the culture to have both a caravan and a caravan insurance.

Contribution to fire policies from 100 to 199

counts <-table(Dummified$`Contribution fire policies_4`, targetFactor) 
barplot(counts,main="Influence of the contribution to fire policies",
        xlab="Wants insurance on caravan", col=c("red","green"),
        legend = c("Has 100 – 199 fire policy","Has different or no policy"), beside=TRUE)

We can see here that those who spend moderately on fire policies (between 100 and 199) are less likely to want to have a caravan.

But if we take a look at the proportions, we may notice something

counts.boat=as.data.frame(counts)

Here, the proportion of boat owners is a lot higher than the proportion of non boat owners.

Conclusion

We notice here that there’s a certain client profile. Those who contribute the most to insurance policies seem to have the “insurance spirit” and seem to be willing to put an insurance on their caravans if they ever have one, thus they are our supposed target. Also, it seems that home renters are more keen on caravans and that is understandable due to the lack of stability of home renters. Home owners tend to be more wealthy thus to work more and have less time for leasure and have less will to move with a caravan.
